WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.510 --> 00:00:07.760
JASON: You guys are obviously
playing Detroit tonight,

00:00:07.760 --> 00:00:08.850
the great city of Detroit.

00:00:08.850 --> 00:00:11.510
So thank you for spending
some time with us.

00:00:11.510 --> 00:00:14.540
I guess since we're on
the topic of the tour,

00:00:14.540 --> 00:00:18.380
maybe we can throw out a
question about the tour.

00:00:18.380 --> 00:00:19.770
I guess Joey, I'm
looking at you.

00:00:19.770 --> 00:00:22.395
So maybe we'll start at that end
and kind of work our way down.

00:00:22.395 --> 00:00:24.980
So you maybe tell us about
what's going on with the tour?

00:00:24.980 --> 00:00:27.050
You guys have been on
the road for, I think,

00:00:27.050 --> 00:00:30.493
a little over a year now,
touring to promote your latest

00:00:30.493 --> 00:00:32.659
album that came out last
year, "Head Carrier," which

00:00:32.659 --> 00:00:34.580
is fantastic.

00:00:34.580 --> 00:00:36.440
What's the tour been like?

00:00:36.440 --> 00:00:39.200
And maybe just to take
that a step further,

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:40.610
how has touring changed?

00:00:40.610 --> 00:00:42.530
What's this tour like
compared to tours

00:00:42.530 --> 00:00:44.270
you guys were doing
in the '80s and '90s,

00:00:44.270 --> 00:00:47.840
besides Paz being here,
and then also tours

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:50.540
that you did in 2004, 2009?

00:00:50.540 --> 00:00:52.460
What's the dynamic like now?

00:00:52.460 --> 00:00:53.550
JOEY: Good question.

00:00:53.550 --> 00:00:55.510
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:57.960 --> 00:00:59.790
Well, the tour's
been going well.

00:00:59.790 --> 00:01:03.810
Everyone's laughing,
doing their own things.

00:01:03.810 --> 00:01:08.010
We get together back in the bus
and go, what did you do today?

00:01:08.010 --> 00:01:09.390
And what did you do?

00:01:09.390 --> 00:01:11.200
And what did you do?

00:01:11.200 --> 00:01:14.006
And then we talk
about what we did.

00:01:14.006 --> 00:01:15.870
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:15.870 --> 00:01:20.980
And then the difference
between now and then

00:01:20.980 --> 00:01:30.950
was, well, we'd be
in the bus and we'd

00:01:30.950 --> 00:01:34.070
wonder where we were and
we'd have to look at the map

00:01:34.070 --> 00:01:38.110
and then look at
the signs and then

00:01:38.110 --> 00:01:41.040
figure out where we were, are.

00:01:41.040 --> 00:01:43.980
We'd have to wake up to do that.

00:01:43.980 --> 00:01:48.390
So now we're in our bunk
and we just go on our phone

00:01:48.390 --> 00:01:51.000
and then go back to sleep.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:52.660
That's the big difference.

00:01:52.660 --> 00:01:55.370
JASON: And I'm assuming you
use Google to figure that out.

00:01:55.370 --> 00:01:56.650
Is that right?

00:01:56.650 --> 00:01:58.360
CHARLES: I don't
even know what it is.

00:01:58.360 --> 00:01:59.800
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:59.800 --> 00:02:01.350
I just ask it.

00:02:01.350 --> 00:02:02.060
We just ask it.

00:02:02.060 --> 00:02:06.870
I just ask it where we
are and it tells me.

00:02:06.870 --> 00:02:07.949
I guess it's Google.

00:02:07.949 --> 00:02:09.199
JASON: It's like magic, right?

00:02:09.199 --> 00:02:10.383
CHARLES: Is it Google?

00:02:10.383 --> 00:02:11.330
JOEY: It's Google.

00:02:11.330 --> 00:02:12.850
JASON: OK, good.

00:02:12.850 --> 00:02:14.134
JOEY: It's on default.

00:02:14.134 --> 00:02:15.050
JASON: That's perfect.

00:02:15.050 --> 00:02:15.580
Good.

00:02:15.580 --> 00:02:17.970
That's the proper
answer, thank you.

00:02:17.970 --> 00:02:19.192
Fantastic.

00:02:19.192 --> 00:02:20.650
Quick show of hands
with the crowd.

00:02:20.650 --> 00:02:25.820
Has anyone here been to
a Pixies show before?

00:02:25.820 --> 00:02:26.554
That's great.

00:02:26.554 --> 00:02:27.220
It's not enough.

00:02:27.220 --> 00:02:29.636
We'll get a few more of you
there this evening, hopefully.

00:02:29.636 --> 00:02:31.980
For those of you who haven't
been to a Pixies show,

00:02:31.980 --> 00:02:34.480
it's a fantastic experience.

00:02:34.480 --> 00:02:36.880
One of my favorite
parts of a Pixies show

00:02:36.880 --> 00:02:39.520
is that there's no set list.

00:02:39.520 --> 00:02:42.850
And what I mean by that is
that the band kind of chooses

00:02:42.850 --> 00:02:47.151
on a whim what's being played
next, usually led by Charles,

00:02:47.151 --> 00:02:47.650
I believe.

00:02:47.650 --> 00:02:52.210
So Charles, maybe tell us a
little bit about that dynamic

00:02:52.210 --> 00:02:55.270
and how you kind of read or
feel the audience or the band's

00:02:55.270 --> 00:02:57.965
energy and decide, hey,
this is the next song

00:02:57.965 --> 00:02:59.590
that I'm going to
throw out to the band

00:02:59.590 --> 00:03:01.360
and we're going to rock it out.

00:03:01.360 --> 00:03:02.276
CHARLES: I don't know.

00:03:02.276 --> 00:03:05.170
I suppose it's just
different all the time.

00:03:05.170 --> 00:03:07.360
I'm having random
thought processes.

00:03:07.360 --> 00:03:12.340
Like oh, that was a song that
mentioned a caribou in it.

00:03:12.340 --> 00:03:14.470
I know, snake.

00:03:14.470 --> 00:03:16.480
Caribou, snake, animals.

00:03:16.480 --> 00:03:18.880
And I'll go on like some animal.

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:21.400
I'll be like, I've got four
animal songs I just did.

00:03:21.400 --> 00:03:23.360
And then monkey, monkey.

00:03:26.050 --> 00:03:28.240
And then sometimes
it'll be like,

00:03:28.240 --> 00:03:31.570
oh yeah, that's a good set-up,
because that song sounds

00:03:31.570 --> 00:03:33.340
like it's talking
about this next song.

00:03:33.340 --> 00:03:35.502
And it will be some
sort of abstract kind

00:03:35.502 --> 00:03:36.460
of a thought like that.

00:03:36.460 --> 00:03:39.940
Or it might be like, oh gee,
they're really not reacting

00:03:39.940 --> 00:03:41.440
to these new songs at all.

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:43.540
We'd better, come on,
let's do the "Here

00:03:43.540 --> 00:03:46.724
Comes Your Man" or something
that's going to perk things

00:03:46.724 --> 00:03:47.390
up a little bit.

00:03:47.390 --> 00:03:51.320
So it just depends on whatever
is going on in my head,

00:03:51.320 --> 00:03:51.820
I guess.

00:03:54.370 --> 00:03:57.010
Sometimes Dave picks one.

00:03:57.010 --> 00:03:59.924
He has a couple drum kind
of nervous energy things

00:03:59.924 --> 00:04:01.840
he'll do that we know
he's getting ready to do

00:04:01.840 --> 00:04:03.590
a certain particular song.

00:04:03.590 --> 00:04:05.430
And it'll be like that one.

00:04:05.430 --> 00:04:08.352
DAVID: And we cheat sometimes,
because some songs go together.

00:04:08.352 --> 00:04:09.310
That goes hand-in-hand.

00:04:09.310 --> 00:04:10.403
That'll happen.

00:04:10.403 --> 00:04:11.249
Visual signs.

00:04:11.249 --> 00:04:12.040
JASON: I like that.

00:04:12.040 --> 00:04:14.650
Keeps the audience on your
toes, but it keeps the band

00:04:14.650 --> 00:04:16.570
on your toes as well, right?

00:04:16.570 --> 00:04:19.329
I read for this
particular tour, you guys

00:04:19.329 --> 00:04:23.530
rehearsed around 90 songs
that at any given time

00:04:23.530 --> 00:04:26.410
you can just kind of
pull out and play.

00:04:26.410 --> 00:04:28.110
Let me direct this
question to you, Paz.

00:04:28.110 --> 00:04:30.400
You're the newest
member of the band,

00:04:30.400 --> 00:04:33.700
here for about a year and
a half, two years now.

00:04:33.700 --> 00:04:35.500
Can you tell us what
that process was

00:04:35.500 --> 00:04:37.930
like once you joined the band?

00:04:37.930 --> 00:04:40.660
How do you learn 90 songs?

00:04:40.660 --> 00:04:43.420
Since you weren't around when
these songs were originally

00:04:43.420 --> 00:04:45.976
written in the '80s and
'90s, you pull these out.

00:04:45.976 --> 00:04:48.100
Is it a little more difficult
for you to kind of go

00:04:48.100 --> 00:04:50.560
through that process, or has
it been fairly simple for you?

00:04:50.560 --> 00:04:52.476
You've obviously played
music for a long time.

00:04:52.476 --> 00:04:54.310
So what's that
been like for you?

00:04:54.310 --> 00:04:58.560
PAZ: I broke my foot and
I couldn't do anything

00:04:58.560 --> 00:05:02.410
except for listen and play.

00:05:02.410 --> 00:05:03.244
So I was in my room.

00:05:03.244 --> 00:05:04.743
This was four years
ago, by the way.

00:05:04.743 --> 00:05:06.310
I've been in the
band for four years.

00:05:06.310 --> 00:05:12.010
And yeah, I was in
my bedroom listening,

00:05:12.010 --> 00:05:16.660
because just to listen
to all of the songs

00:05:16.660 --> 00:05:20.420
would take about five
hours just to listen to it.

00:05:20.420 --> 00:05:23.390
So imagine oh, I wonder
how the bass part goes.

00:05:23.390 --> 00:05:25.470
Then it's another five hours.

00:05:25.470 --> 00:05:28.780
So there goes 10 hours.

00:05:28.780 --> 00:05:34.060
And so yeah, you have to make
sure you're really listening.

00:05:34.060 --> 00:05:36.770
JOEY: I have to apologize, Paz.

00:05:36.770 --> 00:05:38.380
I was the one that
broke your foot.

00:05:38.380 --> 00:05:41.642
PAZ: Yeah, he was like, no,
you're not going anywhere.

00:05:41.642 --> 00:05:42.850
JASON: Is that what kept you?

00:05:42.850 --> 00:05:44.020
Yeah, that's what
got you in the band.

00:05:44.020 --> 00:05:45.645
They broke your foot
and made you stay.

00:05:45.645 --> 00:05:46.930
Is that right?

00:05:46.930 --> 00:05:49.434
Paz, for your first kind
of rehearsal with the band,

00:05:49.434 --> 00:05:51.850
is it true that your mom dropped
you off at the rehearsal?

00:05:51.850 --> 00:05:52.490
Did I hear that correctly?

00:05:52.490 --> 00:05:53.360
PAZ: That's true, yeah.

00:05:53.360 --> 00:05:54.160
JASON: I love this story.

00:05:54.160 --> 00:05:54.970
It's so awesome.

00:05:54.970 --> 00:05:55.886
It's so rock and roll.

00:05:55.886 --> 00:06:01.650
PAZ: My first rehearsal,
this was before we met up

00:06:01.650 --> 00:06:04.200
with Charles in North Hampton.

00:06:04.200 --> 00:06:08.490
We were in California
and my car broke down.

00:06:08.490 --> 00:06:13.840
And I had all my
notes and things.

00:06:13.840 --> 00:06:19.110
I was like, Mom, can you
drop me off at the studio?

00:06:19.110 --> 00:06:21.027
She was so excited.

00:06:21.027 --> 00:06:22.860
I just knew it would
make her super excited.

00:06:22.860 --> 00:06:26.370
She came and picked me
up and dropped me off

00:06:26.370 --> 00:06:29.444
at the rehearsal space in L.A.

00:06:29.444 --> 00:06:30.360
JASON: That's amazing.

00:06:30.360 --> 00:06:30.770
Most of us--

00:06:30.770 --> 00:06:32.019
PAZ: And she picked me up too.

00:06:32.019 --> 00:06:33.360
And she's like, how did it go?

00:06:33.360 --> 00:06:34.746
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:36.600 --> 00:06:38.752
JASON: Obviously well.

00:06:38.752 --> 00:06:40.710
Most of us get dropped
off at the movie theater

00:06:40.710 --> 00:06:41.630
by our parents.

00:06:41.630 --> 00:06:45.670
Paz gets dropped off to join
an amazing rock and roll band.

00:06:45.670 --> 00:06:48.810
Your story is slightly
better than ours.

00:06:48.810 --> 00:06:51.330
David, let me ask you,
on the subject of Paz,

00:06:51.330 --> 00:06:53.740
since we're chatting
with her right now.

00:06:53.740 --> 00:06:55.830
Again, the newest
member of the band.

00:06:55.830 --> 00:06:57.030
Four years, my apologies.

00:06:57.030 --> 00:07:00.120
I cut it a little short, so
I didn't mean to do that.

00:07:00.120 --> 00:07:02.550
Can you talk a little bit
about the dynamic of the band

00:07:02.550 --> 00:07:04.785
and how it's changed
since Paz has joined?

00:07:04.785 --> 00:07:05.910
Obviously she fits in well.

00:07:05.910 --> 00:07:07.320
I'm watching you
guys play for us

00:07:07.320 --> 00:07:08.791
and the dynamic is fantastic.

00:07:08.791 --> 00:07:10.290
Can you talk a
little bit about what

00:07:10.290 --> 00:07:12.134
that's been like to
have her join the group?

00:07:12.134 --> 00:07:13.300
DAVID: Well, it's wonderful.

00:07:13.300 --> 00:07:15.591
Well, she's made me play
better, because she's so good,

00:07:15.591 --> 00:07:17.050
I don't want to be embarrassed.

00:07:17.050 --> 00:07:18.510
I had to step up my game.

00:07:18.510 --> 00:07:20.770
But yeah, it's fantastic.

00:07:20.770 --> 00:07:21.840
She's a joy to be around.

00:07:21.840 --> 00:07:23.269
She plays well.

00:07:23.269 --> 00:07:24.810
And like I've always
said, it's funny

00:07:24.810 --> 00:07:27.702
because she's been
with us for four years.

00:07:27.702 --> 00:07:29.160
She still feels
like the new woman,

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:32.232
so the men are all still
behaving very well.

00:07:32.232 --> 00:07:33.440
JASON: On your best behavior.

00:07:33.440 --> 00:07:34.430
DAVID: Yes.

00:07:34.430 --> 00:07:38.830
JASON: And too, you're the third
female bassist for the band

00:07:38.830 --> 00:07:39.330
as well.

00:07:39.330 --> 00:07:41.430
It's kind of part of
the DNA of the band,

00:07:41.430 --> 00:07:44.970
I suppose, to have a strong
female bassist in there

00:07:44.970 --> 00:07:46.920
as well, which is fantastic.

00:07:46.920 --> 00:07:49.530
Let's get back to the new--

00:07:49.530 --> 00:07:50.940
I call it the new album.

00:07:50.940 --> 00:07:53.080
I guess it's still
new, a year old.

00:07:53.080 --> 00:07:56.910
The newest album, I
suppose, "Head Carrier"

00:07:56.910 --> 00:07:59.550
Charles, maybe for
you, you came out

00:07:59.550 --> 00:08:03.600
with an album a few years
ago, which you kind of

00:08:03.600 --> 00:08:06.120
considered more, I think I read
in an article, a little bit

00:08:06.120 --> 00:08:08.670
more of a transitional
album, where this is kind

00:08:08.670 --> 00:08:12.145
of your return to the
Pixies, this newest

00:08:12.145 --> 00:08:13.020
album "Head Carrier."

00:08:13.020 --> 00:08:15.027
Can you kind of
talk about why you

00:08:15.027 --> 00:08:16.860
feel this album is
different than the albums

00:08:16.860 --> 00:08:18.235
that you've released
in the past,

00:08:18.235 --> 00:08:20.790
or maybe quite similar to some
of the original four albums

00:08:20.790 --> 00:08:21.692
that you released?

00:08:21.692 --> 00:08:23.650
CHARLES: I guess because
we have a bass player.

00:08:23.650 --> 00:08:27.690
In the previous record, we
lost our original bassist

00:08:27.690 --> 00:08:30.450
during the session.

00:08:30.450 --> 00:08:34.010
Anyway, so we had
a friend of ours

00:08:34.010 --> 00:08:37.320
named Ding came to the
session, and he played the bass

00:08:37.320 --> 00:08:38.596
for the rest of the session.

00:08:38.596 --> 00:08:40.679
So we worked it out, but
it was still a little bit

00:08:40.679 --> 00:08:43.589
like, there was this
kind of vacant chair.

00:08:52.410 --> 00:08:57.090
We had booked the studio, and
we were with our old producer

00:08:57.090 --> 00:09:00.040
friend, and we were there.

00:09:00.040 --> 00:09:03.530
We were in this little
village in Wales.

00:09:03.530 --> 00:09:06.510
And it was like, well, we
got to make the record,

00:09:06.510 --> 00:09:08.470
because we've got these
songs and we got this,

00:09:08.470 --> 00:09:10.172
we're in Wales.

00:09:10.172 --> 00:09:11.130
We don't want to leave.

00:09:11.130 --> 00:09:12.780
We just got here.

00:09:12.780 --> 00:09:14.340
So we just did it.

00:09:14.340 --> 00:09:16.590
So it came out the
way it came out.

00:09:16.590 --> 00:09:20.350
And we got through it.

00:09:20.350 --> 00:09:21.870
So yeah, I guess
it was transitional

00:09:21.870 --> 00:09:28.380
because we had this sort of,
we were missing a fourth member

00:09:28.380 --> 00:09:30.730
for that kind of dynamic.

00:09:30.730 --> 00:09:37.810
And so fortunately for
this last session, we did.

00:09:37.810 --> 00:09:38.740
We were like a unit.

00:09:38.740 --> 00:09:47.790
So we're making the coffee
together, hanging out.

00:09:47.790 --> 00:09:51.255
And it was communal
and it was a band.

00:09:51.255 --> 00:09:52.380
JASON: It felt good, right.

00:09:52.380 --> 00:09:53.210
Yeah, absolutely.

00:09:53.210 --> 00:09:55.760
Well, the album is fantastic.

00:09:55.760 --> 00:09:58.140
Has the songwriting
process changed at all?

00:09:58.140 --> 00:10:00.590
You've got the feeling
of a band again.

00:10:00.590 --> 00:10:01.640
You've got a great feel.

00:10:01.640 --> 00:10:03.860
You guys have a great chemistry.

00:10:03.860 --> 00:10:07.190
Has the process, either
of writing the music

00:10:07.190 --> 00:10:09.609
itself, the genesis of
the song or the lyrics,

00:10:09.609 --> 00:10:11.150
has that changed at
all for you guys,

00:10:11.150 --> 00:10:12.410
or is it still fairly similar?

00:10:12.410 --> 00:10:16.580
Does it kind of remain
similar from the '80s

00:10:16.580 --> 00:10:20.142
when you first started writing
and producing music to now?

00:10:20.142 --> 00:10:21.600
CHARLES: I guess
it feels the same.

00:10:21.600 --> 00:10:25.820
I mean, you've got
microphones and tape

00:10:25.820 --> 00:10:27.440
recorders and instruments.

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:32.000
You try to do something that
feels interesting or fun

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:33.170
or something to play.

00:10:33.170 --> 00:10:36.392
And you just, well, we'll
try this one and see how.

00:10:36.392 --> 00:10:38.225
Sometimes it comes back
through the speakers

00:10:38.225 --> 00:10:40.349
and it's like, wow, I didn't
know it was that good.

00:10:40.349 --> 00:10:45.049
And other times it's sort of
like, uh, it's not so good.

00:10:45.049 --> 00:10:45.590
I don't know.

00:10:45.590 --> 00:10:49.040
Every song is different.

00:10:49.040 --> 00:10:54.230
I think I read an interview
years ago with Beck.

00:10:54.230 --> 00:10:57.100
I think he was saying that every
song is like a little country

00:10:57.100 --> 00:10:59.040
and it has its own
rules and customs.

00:10:59.040 --> 00:11:00.460
And I totally understand that.

00:11:00.460 --> 00:11:04.170
So when you start to write a
song, it's like, oh, it's this.

00:11:04.170 --> 00:11:07.880
This is the song, even if
it's not fully matriculated.

00:11:07.880 --> 00:11:10.640
You know what I mean?

00:11:10.640 --> 00:11:12.920
You kind of have a
sense of, oh, that

00:11:12.920 --> 00:11:14.620
follows the customs
of the country.

00:11:14.620 --> 00:11:16.203
And then other times
you try something

00:11:16.203 --> 00:11:19.450
and it's like, that
doesn't fit this country.

00:11:19.450 --> 00:11:23.140
They wouldn't do that there.

00:11:23.140 --> 00:11:26.970
So it's just kind of, I
don't know, that's how it is.

00:11:26.970 --> 00:11:28.440
JASON: And it works, right?

00:11:28.440 --> 00:11:31.131
CHARLES: Yeah, I hope so.

00:11:31.131 --> 00:11:32.630
JASON: You're still
selling tickets,

